{"title_page": "Feminist performance art", "text_new": "{{essay-like|date=November 2017}}\nAccording to scholar Virginia Mackenny, [[performance art]] is a great tool to mold and remold gender because performance art, in most instances, includes a direct subversion to everyday conventions. MacKenny also writes that feminist performance Art had a large presence \u201cin the late '60s and early '70s in America when, in the climate of protest constituted by the civil rights movement and [[second wave feminism]].\" There are several movements that fall under the category of feminist performance art, including Feminist Postmodernism, which took place during 1960-1970 and focused on the exploitation of women's bodies as a means for profit. Similarly, the Chicanx movement emerged in East Los Angeles during the 1970s, and focused on the Vietnam war, which was considered a post-apartheid movement.<ref name=\"MacKenny\">{{cite journal|last1=MacKenny|first1=Virginia|title=Post - Apartheid Performance Art as a Site of Gender Resistance|journal=Agenda Empowering Women for Gender Equity|date=2001|volume=49|pages=15\u201324|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n== Feminist Postmodernism ==\nAs Forte writes in her analysis of feminist performance art in the 1960s and 1970s, \u201cWithin this movement, women's performance emerges as a specific strategy that allies [[postmodernism]] and [[feminism]] \u2026 women used performance as a deconstructive strategy to demonstrate the objectification of women and its results\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Forte|first1=Jeanie|title=Women's Performance Art: Feminism and Postmodernism|journal=Theatre Journal|date=1988|volume=40.2|issn=0192-2882}}</ref> Another strategy that was commonly used by feminist performance artists during the postmodernist movement was \u201cremoving of the mask,\u201d which was utilized to demonstrate the consequences of female representations in the media, on the psyche of women. MacKenny also writes about the removing of the mask within Feminist Postmodernism. She writes, \u201cThis 'masquerade' or 'masking' occurs when women play with their assigned gender roles in multiple, often contradictory ways - adopting, adapting, overlaying and subverting the hegemonic discourse in the process.\u201d\n\n== Chicanx Movement ==\nDuring the late 1960s and early 1970s in East Los Angeles, protests broke out against the [[Vietnam War]] and its disproportionate death rate of 22% Chicanx people, while the percentage of the population that Chicanx people made up only 5% of the United States entire population.\n[[Asco (art collective)]], based in [[East Los Angeles, California|East LA]] commented on the impacts of the war on [[queer]] and brown identities, as well as the tragedies that occurred in the protests discussed above due to [[police brutality]]. The collective created visual and performative art. Some of their most famous performances experiment with gender roles, for example, one male identifying artist attended a club wearing \u201cbooty shorts, pink platforms, and a shirt that said \u2018just turned 21.\u2019\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perez|first1=Laura E.|title=Chicana art: the politics of spiritual and aesthetic altarities|date=2007|publisher=Durham: Duke U|isbn=978-0-8223-8988-0|doi=10.1215/9780822389880}}</ref>\nThe group continued to make performance and visual art that engaged with concepts related to queer and [[ethnic identity]] in East LA. During this period, East LA was ghettoized through a border of highways and dilapidated conditions.\n\n== Post Apartheid Movement ==\nMacKenny writes about two of the major players in the Post [[Apartheid]] performance art movement in [[South Africa]]. She first writes about Carol Anne Gainer and her performance entitled 'Exposed.' MacKenny explains that Gainer disrupts and subverts the binary as she performs as both the model and artist in this performance, which works to blur the \"distinction between artist/art, artist/model, constructor/constructed, finder/found, mind/body, subject/object.\"\nThe second artist which Mackenny writes about is a [[mixed race]] artist who performs a piece called 'Span.' MacKenny asserts that the artist Tracey Rose, alludes to Western societies exploitation of people of colour in scientific study and analysis, and the \"dissection and embalming of body parts of native 'others' (the most pertinent to the South African context being Saartje Baartman, a young Khoisan woman displayed for her unique genitalia and steatopygia, or enlarged buttocks),\" through her own display of her body.<ref name=\"MacKenny\"/> Her performance exposes her naked body and is contrasted against images of \"scientific\" exploitation, which both highlights the dichotomy between these subjects and engages with Mackenny's definition of post-apartheid performance art and its political aim to blur and disrupt binary structures.\n\n=== Anti War Performance Art Movement ===\nThe sociologist Rachel V Kutz-Flamenbaum writes about two major players in the anti-war performance art movement during the George W Bush administration. Code Pink, and Raging Grannies challenge and subvert gender norms in their performances, and thus, use very similar tactics and strategies. For instance, in Code Pink, Kutz-Flamenbaum asserts that, \"the emphasis on women\u2019s role as pacifist caregivers presents a nonthreatening image of women activists.\" \n\nThe perpetuated concept of women as non threatening, relies on the audiences association of pink as a non threatening and feminized colour. Kutz-Flamenbaum argues that \"Code Pink\u2019s use of civil disobedience and aggressive trailing of public officials confound and challenge normative gender expectations of women as passive, polite, and well-behaved.\"(95)<ref name=\"Kutz-Flamenbaum\">{{cite journal|last1=Kutz-Flamenbaum|first1=Rachel V|title=Code Pink, Raging Grannies, and the Missile Dick Chicks: Feminist Performance Activism in the Contemporary Anti-War Movement|journal=NWSA Journal|date=Spring 2001|volume=19|issue=1|pages=90\u201396|issn=1040-0656}}</ref>\nKutz-Flamenbaum claims that [[Raging Grannies]] similarly use this tactic in the description of their mission statement. Kutz-Flamenbaum explains that their mission statement \"illustrates the way Raging Grannies use norm- embracing stereotypes of 'little old ladies' and 'grannies' to challenge the gendered assumptions of their audiences.\" Their conscious performance as non-threatening and nurturing women, strategically and tactfully confront issues related to war and challenge the participation of the George W Bush administration in the war. \n\n== Performance Artists ==\n\n===[[Soad Hosny]]===\n[[File:Suad Husni.jpg|thumb|Suad Husni in 1972 from her movie \"Khalli Balak Min Zoozoo\" (watch out for Zoozoo)]]\n[[Soad Hosny]] (January 26, 1943 \u2013 June 21, 2001)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elfagr.news/2442336|title=\u0634\u0627\u0647\u062f.. \u0634\u0647\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a|website=\u0628\u0648\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u062c\u0631|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> is an Egyptian actress and singer named the \"Cinderella of Egyptian Cinema\".<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://login.colorado.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://bi.gale.com%2fglobal%2farticle%2fGALE%257CA569882059%3fu%3dcoloboulder%26sid%3dsummon|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.colorado.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In her 32 year long career, Hosny preformed in more than [[Soad Hosny filmography|83 films]] and a single TV series called \"Hekayat Hwa we Heya\".<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://https//elcinema.com/en/person/1097577|title=Soad Hosny - Actor Filmography\u060c photos\u060c Video|website=elCinema.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\":03\" />\n\n==== Feminist works ====\n\n===== \"Lilregal Faqat\" =====\nIn 1964, she and [[Nadia Lutfi]] acted in the movie \"Lilregal Faqat\" (For Men Only), which discusses woman's ability to take on jobs that are stereotypically masculine.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allam|first=Nermin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pck-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=feminist+film+%22+lel+regal+fakat%22&source=bl&ots=j-t04-XqFe&sig=ACfU3U34aedePx32Yscd_egNBCUbmDn4og&hl=ar&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj4xZqBuOToAhVYnp4KHburC60Q6AEwAXoECAsQLQ#v=onepage&q=feminist%20film%20%22%20lel%20regal%20fakat%22&f=false|title=Women and the Egyptian Revolution: Engagement and Activism during the 2011 Arab Uprisings|date=2018|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-108-42190-4|language=en}}</ref> In the movie, Soad and Nadia play the roles of two lab workers who report oil-wills locations based on samples they get from the desert. When the male workers in the desert don't find any oil in the locations reported by the two women, they disguise as men and go to the digging-site in the desert.<ref>{{Citation|title=Movie - Lilregal Faqat - 1964 Cast\u060c Video\u060c Trailer\u060c photos\u060c Reviews\u060c Showtimes|url=https://https//elcinema.com/en/work/1001879|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=\u0641\u064a\u0644\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u0631\u062c\u0627\u0644 \u0641\u0642\u0637 {{!}} \u0641\u064a\u0644\u0645 \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a {{!}} \u0628\u0637\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u0649 \u0648 \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hM-FAaGK2zU|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=For Men Only|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0376725/|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n===== \"Hekayat Hwa we Heya\" =====\n\"Hekayat Hwa we Heya\" (The Stories of Him and Her) is a 1985 TV series that revolves around the relationships between the two genders and gender equality.<ref name=\":03\" /><ref name=\":12\" /> In the episode titled \"Garas el Fusha\", Soad perforemed one of her most popular songs, \"elbanat elbanat \" (Girls Girls).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.colorado.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://go.gale.com%2fps%2fi.do%3fp%3dITOF%26u%3dcoloboulder%26id%3dGALE%257CA517578690%26v%3d2.1%26it%3dr%26sid%3dITOF%26asid%3d31a8495c|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.colorado.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> This kids' song raised the equality slogan with phrases like \"Girls are like boys\" and \"we are happy to be born girls\", as it praised girls emphasising that they are smart, talented, strong, wise, beautiful, and kind...etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genderiyya.xyz/wiki/\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a_\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a|title=\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=\u0647\u0648 \u0648\u0647\u064a: \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a .. \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a .. \u0644\u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RDKP_x9dn0w|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Other ====\nIn addition to her direct call for women's rights in some of her works, the Egyptian Cinderella's feminine lively personality, youthful soul, and kind heart encouraged girls to idolise her and gain pride in their gender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.colorado.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://bi.gale.com%2fglobal%2farticle%2fGALE%257CA543828738%3fu%3dcoloboulder%26sid%3dsummon|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.colorado.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2006, [[Mona Zaki]] played the role of Soad Hosny in the biography TV series Named \"Cinderella\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Series - Cinderella - 2006 Cast\u060c Video\u060c Trailer\u060c photos\u060c Reviews\u060c Showtimes|url=https://https//elcinema.com/en/work/1696997|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Commenting on it in one of her interviews, Mona Zaki said that she was a tomboyish kid, and was shy of her feminine features at her early teens, but playing the role of Soad Hosny triggered her pride in being a woman, as it was a turning point in her feelings towards her femininity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynewsarabia.com/varieties/524383-%D9%85%D9%86%D9%89-%D8%B2%D9%83%D9%8A-%D8%B3%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%86%D9%8A-%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B1|title=\u0645\u0646\u0649 \u0632\u0643\u064a: \u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a \u0644\u0645 \u062a\u0646\u062a\u062d\u0631|website=\u0633\u0643\u0627\u064a \u0646\u064a\u0648\u0632 \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><br />\n== [[Frida Kahlo]] ==\nFrida Kahlo's work as an artist remained relatively unknown until the late 1970s to most people outside of Mexico and Latin America, when her work was rediscovered by art historians and political activists she, her art, and her role as a performance artist was brought to the forefront of the art world. In the early 1990s, Kahlo had become a recognized figure in art history, but also regarded as an icon for [[Chicano Movement|Chicana/os]], the [[Latinx]]<nowiki/>community, the [[feminism]]<nowiki/>movement, and the [[LGBTQ+]]<nowiki/>movement. Kahlo's work is celebrated internationally as emblematic of Mexican nationalism and [[Indigenous peoples of Mexico|indigenous]]<nowiki/>traditions and by feminists for what is seen as its uncompromising depiction of the female experience and form.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Broude|first=Norma|url=http://archive.org/details/expandingdiscour00norm|title=The Expanding discourse : feminism and art history|last2=Garrard|first2=Mary D.|date=1992|publisher=New York, NY : IconEditions|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> While she is definitely Mexican, Kahlo is regarded as an icon for Chicana/os who recognize themselves as the hyphen in the middle of the label of Mexican - American. Her depictions of being a person limited by her realities are expressed in her surreal style, which appeal to a broad audience of people from many walks of life.\n\nAlthough [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]], a [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] artist, regarded her primarily as a 'feminista' within the Surrealist movement, Kahlo brought postcolonial issues to the forefront of her brand of Surrealism<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418093138/https://repository.asu.edu/attachments/107983/content/JSA_VOL5_NO1_Pages33-54_Mahon.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2018-04-18|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. Her understanding and visions of being, living with the disabilities she suffered from a trolley accident in her younger years resonate with those also afflicted with disabilities. Her portrayal of herself as a person of color, living the realities of a person limited by her gender, disabilities and a dissident politico made her appealing to an audience previously absent to the art scene. Her art raised the questions of identity. What was it to be a Mexican? \u2013 modern, yet pre-Columbian; young, yet old; anti-Catholic yet Catholic; Western, yet New World; developing, yet underdeveloped; independent, yet colonized; ''mestizo'', yet not Spanish nor Indian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809095503/https://www.gen2.ca/DBHS/Art/3346753.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|last=Bakewell 1993, pg. 169|first=|date=2017-08-09|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n[[File:Las Dos Fridas.jpg|thumb|The Two Fridas, 1939]]\nOriana Baddeley has written that Kahlo has become a signifier of non-conformity and \"the archetype of a cultural minority,\" who is regarded simultaneously as \"a victim, crippled and abused\" and as \"a survivor who fights back.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baddeley|first=St. Clair|date=1897-01-16|title=Waterspout and Whirlwind|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/nq/s8-xi.264.47a|journal=Notes and Queries|volume=s8-XI|issue=264|pages=47\u201347|doi=10.1093/nq/s8-xi.264.47a|issn=1471-6941}}</ref> Edward Sullivan stated that Kahlo is hailed as a hero by so many because she is \"someone to validate their own struggle to find their own voice and their own public personalities\".<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2004|editor-last=Kauffman|editor-first=Kyle D.|editor2-last=Lindauer|editor2-first=David L.|title=AIDS and South Africa|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1057/9780230523517|doi=10.1057/9780230523517}}</ref> According to [[John Berger]], Kahlo's popularity is partly due to the fact that \"the sharing of pain is one of the essential preconditions for a refinding of dignity and hope\" in twenty-first century society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brock\u2010Servais|first=Rhonda|date=2001|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1023/a:1010417217654|journal=Children's Literature in Education|volume=32|issue=3|pages=155\u2013165|doi=10.1023/a:1010417217654|issn=0045-6713}}</ref> She did not use them only to show her subjective experience but to raise questions about Mexican society and the construction of identity within it, particularly gender, race, and social class.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809095503/https://www.gen2.ca/DBHS/Art/3346753.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|last=Bakewell 1993 pg. 168-170|first=|date=2017-08-09|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Frida has become almost saint like to many and a symbol, a feeling to people who like her, have experienced questioning their identity, their place in a society that does not accept difference readily. Her paintings evoke a sense pride in being of Mexican heritage for many and an acceptance for those who have struggled in life.   \n\n\n==[[Yoko Ono]]==\n\n=== Overview ===\nOno belonged to a generation of early feminist performance artists but is unique among them for her international fame as [[John Lennon]]\u2019s wife in the late 60s and 70s.  During their courtship the couple manipulated the press attention directed on them by documenting their relationship through performance art.<ref name=\":0\">Elizabeth Ann Lindau. \u201cMother Superior\u201d: Maternity and Creativity in the Work of Yoko Ono.\" ''Women and Music: A Journal of Gender and Culture'' 20 (University of Nebraska Press: 2016), 64.</ref> As Ono stated in a 1986 TV interview, \u201cwe were always together\u2026 we exchanged very fully between ourselves.\u201d<ref name=\":1\">''Yoko Ono on John Lennon's Assasination, Their Son Sean and Influencing The Beatles Breakup.'', ''YouTube'' (YouTube, 2017), <nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Suj8MCysBKQ</nowiki>)</ref> They emphasized this unusual situation, where the husband and wife worked together rather than the pair working separately outside the home, through their performance art \u201cBed-ins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs an interracial couple they also challenged racial stereotypes. She confessed, \u201cI think it was a big lesson for the world that we were together\u2026 And I think it might have helped too for people to understand what it means to confront the interracial couple.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nParenthood is a factor in the controversy surrounding Ono. Women were not usually part of performance art or rock music, and mothers in particular were antithetical to everything rock stood for. The public idea of rock music as youthful male rebellion placed mothers as the opponent. When Ono and Lennon began their relationship, Beatles fans saw this female influence as an intrusion and the force that broke up their favorite band. However, as Ono saw it, the [[The Beatles|Beatles]] grew apart naturally and she was not the primary cause.<ref name=\":1\" /> Public confusion was exacerbated with Ono\u2019s pregnancy. While pregnant with their son Sean, Ono announced to Lennon: \u201cI am carrying the baby nine months and that is enough. You take care of it afterwards.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> After Sean\u2019s birth, she ran the couple\u2019s business while Lennon stayed home as \u201chousehusband.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Ono\u2019s hands off approach to parenting is a source of controversy because she was simultaneously too motherly and not motherly enough.\n\n=== Work ===\nOne of her early works is [[Cut Piece]], first performed in 1964 at the Yamaichi Concert Hall in Kyoto. She kneeled on the stage in her best suit and invited audience members to use scissors to cut it off of her. Confronting issues of gender, class and cultural identity, Ono sat silently until the piece concluded at her discretion.<ref>Munroe, Alexandra; Ono, Yoko; Hendricks, Jon; Altshuler, Bruce; Ross, David A.; Wenner, Jann S.; Concannon, Kevin C.; Tomii, Reiko; Sayle, Murray; Gomez, Edward M. (October 2000). Yes Yoko Ono. New York: Harry N. Abrams. {{ISBN|0-81094-587-8}}.</ref> Ono also published a book of conceptual art in 1964, entitled [[Grapefruit (book)|Grapefruit]]. The book reads like an instruction manual for the reader to create their own versions of her pieces either physically or in the imagination. Over the nearly 60 years that she has been active, Ono has created installations of modern art across the globe, recorded numerous original songs both with John Lennon and the [[Plastic Ono Band]], as well as individually, and continues in activism to this day.\n\n== Orlan==\nORLAN (born as Mireille Suzanne Francette Porte) is French performance artist, most known for her radical use of plastic surgery to form her work. She uses her face and body as a malleable tool to change her appearance and therefore change her art. She primarily used plastic surgery to morph and change her body in her theatrical expression. Orlan uses her body at the heart of her expression, to articulate her political, social and cultural beliefs. Due to suffering an ectopic pregnancy, she felt her body was changed dramatically, and through that, she chose to turn her body into artwork through the use of plastic surgery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/orlan/|title=ORLAN {{!}} artnet|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOne of her most notable performances was that of the 1977 International Contemporary Art Fair in Paris. On her exterior, she had a large photo of a torso on her chest. This was turned into a slot machine, where the audience could put a coin down the slot and watch it descend into the groin. As a reward, that audience member were given a kiss. She also displayed her sexual organs during menstruation under a magnifying glass for respective audience members to study. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Donger|first=Simon|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XoXFBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=orlan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyw_Da7snoAhVxlFwKHZmmAdsQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=orlan&f=false|title=ORLAN: A Hybrid Body of Artworks|last2=Shepherd|first2=Simon|date=2010-05-20|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-97128-0|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Bj\u00f6rk Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir ==\nThe musical artist Bj\u00f6rk has been challenging musical barriers since her time in the band [[The Sugarcubes]], which became the biggest alternative rock band in Iceland. She has since gone on to a solo career, starting in 1993 with the album [[Debut (Bj\u00f6rk album)|''Debut'']] with her last album having been released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bj%C3%B6rk-mn0000769444/biography|title=Bj\u00f6rk {{!}} Biography & History|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> She throughout her time has used her music to speak on matters she deemed important while following a unique and individualistic style for each of her albums. She finds something that she finds challenging or that she dislikes and work with it to create something she's proud of, allowing her to continue having these unique albums.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4143741-interview--bjork-talks-piracy-punk-lady-gaga-and-biophilia|title=Interview: Bjork talks piracy, punk, Lady Gaga and Biophilia|last=October 9th|first=Kevin EG Perry|last2=2011|website=DrownedInSound|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== ''Biophilia and Environmental Work'' ===\nThis has lead to one of her most famous albums ''[[Biophilia (album)|Biophilia]]'' which was Bj\u00f6rk's two year long passion project to give her music a more visual and hands on feel. The album was developed into an iPad and iPod app that allowed users to listen to each song while playing games that visually showcased the music. The most notable example is the song \u2018Thunderbolt\u2019  which allows listeners to draw \"Tesla coil charges which alter the bass lines you hear\" and when she performs the song live she has twin Tesla coils to play the bass line.<ref name=\":2\" /> This album however was more than a challenge for Bj\u00f6rk to create a new sound, she created the album as a response to the environmental issues Iceland was facing in 2008. Iceland had allowed the aluminum smelters to take over the countries fishing industry while being the cause for excessive greenhouse gas emissions. Her goal was to create an album that could educate people about the world we are living in and inspire them to take actions against companies that work to destroy the planet.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/07/bjork-environmental-campaign-timetable-nordic-schools|title=Bj\u00f6rk's environmental campaign goes on the timetable in Nordic schools|date=2014-06-07|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=arts|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|last3=correspondent|first3=media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/11/13/bjork-wages-battle-against-icelandic-aluminum/|title=Bj\u00f6rk Wages Battle Against Icelandic Aluminum|last=Kanter|first=James|date=2008-11-13|website=Green Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== 'Declare Independence' and Activism ===\nThis environmental work would not be the only time she has used her music and voice to speak out as the song 'Declare Independence' would often be a song she would use to speak out for the freedom of nations trying to seceded from the nations they have been forced to be apart of. Most notable was when she, unauthorized, sang the song in her Shanghai concert in 2008, chanting Tibet in the middle of the song.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7276891.stm|title=Bjork makes 'free Tibet' gesture|date=2008-03-04|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> At the time Tibet was revolting against China for its freedom, and as such her use of the song caused many concert goers to leave the venue and the Chinese government to tighten their regulations for all outside performers from then on. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7293605.stm|title=Western acts 'welcome' in China|date=2008-03-13|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Lady Gaga ==\nLady Gaga (Stefani Joanne Angelina Germanotta) has experimented and incorporated performance art into her life. Her first internet appearance in performance art came in 2013 in a kickstarter for \u201cThe Abromovic Method\u201d ran by Marina Abromovic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/71937056|title=The Abramovic Method Practiced by Lady Gaga|website=Vimeo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>This video was taken during a physical and spiritual retreat she participated that was hosted by Abromovic at her summer home. Gaga is featured \u201cfilling the room\u201d with her voice and wandering naked in the woods. Gaga was asked to test her body and go through strenuous activities. She also added to the piece by participating fully and even suggesting additions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://culturacolectiva.com/art/lady-gaga-marina-abramovic-collaboration|title=The Day Lady Gaga Stripped To Please Marina Abramovic and Be Free From Drugs|date=2017-01-30|website=culturacolectiva.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Abbromovic reported she was a very compliant student. Later, Gaga fit performance art into her 2011 Video Music Awards appearance. She showed up to perform her song \u201cYou and I\u201d dressed up as a person deemed Jo Calderone. <ref>{{Citation|title=Jo Calderone (Lady Gaga) You And I Live - VMAs 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SkWoA25V4tQ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> When speaking, she spoke with a Brooklyn accent and walk, and spoke as a typical man. She commented that performance art meant fully committing and diving into a character including, acting as the character the whole night. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1669957/lady-gaga-jo-calderone-vmas/|title=Why Did Lady Gaga Go To VMAs As Jo Calderone?|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>They finished their speech at the award show talking about the importance of accepting people for who they are with no discrimination, because it was they way they were born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-339-1286022|title=Lady Gaga performs as male alter ego Jo Calderone at MTV VMAs {{!}} NME|date=2011-08-29|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Later Gaga dabbled with the performance art of \u201cCamp\u201d at the 2019 Met Gala. \"Camp\" is a form of performance art through clothing that stems from the drag culture and is meant to tell a story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://depauliaonline.com/41447/artslife/camp-the-theme-that-means-the-most-or-nothing-at-all/|title=Camp: the theme that means the most \u2013 or nothing at all|last=Oxnevad|first=Emma|date=2019-05-13|website=The DePaulia|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance through clothing ====\nHer outfit for the Met Gala consisted of four overlapping outfits that she stripped from one to the next while on the red carpet for the Gala.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peters|first=Micheal A|date=January 2012|title=On the Edge of Theory: Lady Gaga, performance and cultural theory|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwVV3NCsIwDC6yg7_vEPAkOLGuW1tvIv6B4EW9jmzddlNxevDtTdyGeuolCaVNkyZNvnaFR3Fr1hKdmYy48yOcefywq_hcBbrd5D8YZ0YF045YHC5Adx3g9BFcc_g08L3msEf3gg0WOIbbt4YeKL6GBpSipu0L73F_ZoNq6InTenVcbv36MwG_YFAqPzQJ6Sqiy6RLlMxDY8n1WtQBzVBl1jolU0PeNpeJY5ASIjaJZguvXW74Y91hJbcx2XG92-UHZNNMtY0YfHBSUbF9j1lJHndMsa51p4VhuKV4wWIVO1NiGP0xcIU6meUCn2UZ7w7nX9o339xjrg|journal=Contemporary readings in Law and social Justice|volume=4|pages=1|via=}}</ref> The outfits consisted of black and pink and had a coy, classic femme aesthetic.She also had a team providing her with props like a suitcase, wagon and 90\u2019s telephone. She also represented performance art on a mainstream platform with two separate VMA appearances. One was in 2010, when she wore a \u201cmeat dress\u201d to the show. The dress consisted of prime rib and flank steak. The dress was referencing a speech \u201cThe Prime Rib of America\u201d, that encouraged the end of discrimination against gay men and women in the military and Gaga stated the military denies them \u201c the greatest cut of meat my country has to offer.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/lady-gaga-meat-dress-explanation|title=Getting Political|website=British Vogue|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The second was the Joe Calerone one previously mentioned, both performed with intent of raising awareness to a cause.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kumari|first=Ashanka|date=April 2016|title=\"You and I\"|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMw42JgAfZbUxkgJ4GCF80UJJfqAasRA1Mm0NmlJga6ppbGwDwEPcUb2MPggBWdwNaEASdDwKOGOZH5h_coAPvSCp6PGuZaKUB3rVaChYAtI4UAxLJ6hfw0heDUnDSFzDwFn8SUSgX3xPREsELwJpDkwyt5GFhKikpTeSEUN0Oom2uIs4cu9LYBXVCVZ6prngwszFMNLcyTjdIsDI2TzE2SUlIsLU2NUkySk43NTYEJNTHVJDUl0SQ5CbQdNBlYV6aapYAyhWliYhro4nUtiLmw-i2-AHJgRDy8oQ0MiXhwSAAVq0IVo0x2xyeCphvig4ANKVDWAF2iZAhRB2454zEx3ivAORRiNgDmtXCK|journal=The Journal of Pop Culture|volume=49|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance of her own feminism ====\nShe preaches about equality to all through the removing of labels and just treating people as people. Her main message is to spread kindness over all else.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jennex|first=Craig|date=July 2013|title=Diva Worship and the Sonic Search for Queer Utopia|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwfV09DwIhDCXmBj__A4sjBo7qweTgR1z9uDgSUEicNOb090vhjLo4sRRIF9pH2_f6pIi41ZN2Sg1prGXijMF-ACEnlVZTgE4aU-RMVKIs0j8_Z2jT_TyiHHqkXF6elh6vqaOXRmhNY1ZE90gaS3M7Lo2pHd1GzHendXO9XeyQFM394Ud5GZB6vTosNqxVFmAnyRWwADNnBaCanXBVlVjDtJKOSzs7O-twHFW7ABq8kFaBdlB6OPMgrPcyoMg65HPfsczcMjmEEW_OzdZrg16b7HXcNm63_ZS4jcUig9nFbD3Gb4V282z3zZ5qmoThQxbcMPLvTS-VRmpL|journal=Popular Music and Society: Fandom|volume=36|pages=3|via=}}</ref> She believes women have the right to choose the life they see fit for themselves, even if it means dependent on others. She is also a big advocate for sexual assault awareness as she is a survivor herself. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Corona|first=Victor P.|date=2013|title=Memory, Monsters, and Lady Gaga|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|journal=The Journal of Popular Culture|language=en|volume=46|issue=4|pages=725\u2013744|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|issn=1540-5931}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== The Guerrilla Girls ==\nThe Guerrilla Girls formed in New York City in the mid 1980s.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/guerrilla-girls-6858|title=Guerrilla Girls|last=Tate|website=Tate|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>The Guerrilla Girls focused their performances, protests, installations, and exhibits on highlighting the lack of representation of women and people of color within the art world.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> Most notably, The Guerrilla Girls donned gorilla masks and costumes during protest in order to maintain anonymity, and to make their work more about the issues rather than each member\u2019s own identity.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nAfter protesting the lack of diversity at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City in 1985, the Guerrilla Girls expanded their work into prints, billboards, public commissions, and, indoor exhibitions. This also came with their work focusing on a wider array of issues such as the wage gap, tokenism, and funding for the arts.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> The public performances of the Guerrilla Girls in the early days took the form of protest, by wearing their gorilla masks and conducting \"weenie counts\" in museums, where the members would count he male to female work and subject ratios. Most notably in 1989 they found that The Met's public collections only had 5% of their works produced by women, while 85% of the works including nudity focused on a nude female. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref>\n\nThe Guerrilla Girls have been met with criticism and backlash. While they focus on the issue of diversity, it has been said that the majority of the members are white. Former member, Alma Thomas have noted the lack of effort in understanding the challenges faced by artists of color by other members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-guerrilla-girls-zora-neale-hurston-and-agnes-martin-15840|title=Oral history interview with Guerrilla Girls Zora Neale Hurston and Agnes Martin, 2008 May 17|website=www.aaa.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The Guerrilla Girls have also been accused of \u201cselling out,\u201d having their works shown at the same hegemonic establishments that they protested in the past.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/guerrilla-girl-power-have-americas-feminist-artists-sold-out-1666140.html|title=Guerrilla girl power: Have America's feminist artists sold out?|date=2009-04-09|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== [[Ana Mendieta]] ==\n\n=== Overview ===\nMendieta's work was greatly informed by the part of her identity that was embedded in the term \"immigrant\". She's widely known for her performance art and art book full of her pieces called ''Traces''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-in-america/interviews/the-untold-ana-mendieta-56344/|title=The Untold: Ana Mendieta|last=Donnelly|first=Ryann|last2=Donnelly|first2=Ryann|date=2013-10-08|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>''.'' Her immigration from Cuba to the USA was full of displacement and separation from her homeland and many of her family members for a long period of time. This inspired her future work to explore the aspects of belonging, estrangement, feminism, life, death, violence and overall the rawness of the natural of femininity and the earth. Her fascinations with natures elements: water, fire, earth, air and the flesh were interwoven into her performance art work. She was a huge part of the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/body-art/ body art movement] which was it's own form that grew as a branch off from the trunk of performance art<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theartstory.org/artist/mendieta-ana/|title=Ana Mendieta Art, Bio, Ideas|website=The Art Story|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Furthermore, she was seen as a huge contributor to the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/earth-art/ land art movement] which she often paired with her body art to create her feminist and identity messages in her performance art pieces<ref name=\":3\" />. Her untimely death at 36 years old left audiences hurting for more, but some of her pieces still stand in art studios today such as [[Alison Jacques Gallery]] and are incorporated in conversations about feminist and immigrant artwork<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alisonjacquesgallery.com/exhibitions/|title=Gallery Programme|website=Alison Jacques Gallery|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>.<br />    \n\n== Gesel Mason ==\nGesel Mason is choreographer, educator, performer, and arts facilitator. Currently, she is the Artistic Director of Gesel Mason Performance Projects and an Associate Professor at the University of Texas at Austin. Gesel has performed for and been a member of numerous well-established choreographers and companies. In her work, Mason utilizes dance, theater, humor, and storytelling to bring visibility to those voices unheard, situation neglected, or perspectives considered taboo. Mason has cultivated a multitude of works and performances including her highlighted projects; Women, Desire, & Sex, antithesis, and No Boundaries.\n\n==== No Boundaries ====\n\n==== antithesis ====\n\n==== Women, Sex, & Desire ====\nWomen, Sex, & Desire: Sometime You Feel Like a Ho, Sometimes You Dont is an interactive performance addressing how women navigate desire, sex, percepion, and choice. This multi-media performance consists of a comedy sketch, part talk show, workshop retreat, and dance performance. Mason creates a raw and personalized experience for the audience along with her dancers by combining their real stories, people, and movement ranging from postmodern to pole dancing. Mason began the dialogue of the delight and frustrations of being a sexual creature. Mason uses Women, Sex, & Desire to create a safe environment for people to expose their vulnerability while incorporating an entertaining, raw, insightful, and risky experience. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Feminist art]]\n", "text_old": "{{essay-like|date=November 2017}}\nAccording to scholar Virginia Mackenny, [[performance art]] is a great tool to mold and remold gender because performance art, in most instances, includes a direct subversion to everyday conventions. MacKenny also writes that feminist performance Art had a large presence \u201cin the late '60s and early '70s in America when, in the climate of protest constituted by the civil rights movement and [[second wave feminism]].\" There are several movements that fall under the category of feminist performance art, including Feminist Postmodernism, which took place during 1960-1970 and focused on the exploitation of women's bodies as a means for profit. Similarly, the Chicanx movement emerged in East Los Angeles during the 1970s, and focused on the Vietnam war, which was considered a post-apartheid movement.<ref name=\"MacKenny\">{{cite journal|last1=MacKenny|first1=Virginia|title=Post - Apartheid Performance Art as a Site of Gender Resistance|journal=Agenda Empowering Women for Gender Equity|date=2001|volume=49|pages=15\u201324|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n== Feminist Postmodernism ==\nAs Forte writes in her analysis of feminist performance art in the 1960s and 1970s, \u201cWithin this movement, women's performance emerges as a specific strategy that allies [[postmodernism]] and [[feminism]] \u2026 women used performance as a deconstructive strategy to demonstrate the objectification of women and its results\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Forte|first1=Jeanie|title=Women's Performance Art: Feminism and Postmodernism|journal=Theatre Journal|date=1988|volume=40.2|issn=0192-2882}}</ref> Another strategy that was commonly used by feminist performance artists during the postmodernist movement was \u201cremoving of the mask,\u201d which was utilized to demonstrate the consequences of female representations in the media, on the psyche of women. MacKenny also writes about the removing of the mask within Feminist Postmodernism. She writes, \u201cThis 'masquerade' or 'masking' occurs when women play with their assigned gender roles in multiple, often contradictory ways - adopting, adapting, overlaying and subverting the hegemonic discourse in the process.\u201d\n\n== Chicanx Movement ==\nDuring the late 1960s and early 1970s in East Los Angeles, protests broke out against the [[Vietnam War]] and its disproportionate death rate of 22% Chicanx people, while the percentage of the population that Chicanx people made up only 5% of the United States entire population.\n[[Asco (art collective)]], based in [[East Los Angeles, California|East LA]] commented on the impacts of the war on [[queer]] and brown identities, as well as the tragedies that occurred in the protests discussed above due to [[police brutality]]. The collective created visual and performative art. Some of their most famous performances experiment with gender roles, for example, one male identifying artist attended a club wearing \u201cbooty shorts, pink platforms, and a shirt that said \u2018just turned 21.\u2019\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perez|first1=Laura E.|title=Chicana art: the politics of spiritual and aesthetic altarities|date=2007|publisher=Durham: Duke U|isbn=978-0-8223-8988-0|doi=10.1215/9780822389880}}</ref>\nThe group continued to make performance and visual art that engaged with concepts related to queer and [[ethnic identity]] in East LA. During this period, East LA was ghettoized through a border of highways and dilapidated conditions.\n\n== Post Apartheid Movement ==\nMacKenny writes about two of the major players in the Post [[Apartheid]] performance art movement in [[South Africa]]. She first writes about Carol Anne Gainer and her performance entitled 'Exposed.' MacKenny explains that Gainer disrupts and subverts the binary as she performs as both the model and artist in this performance, which works to blur the \"distinction between artist/art, artist/model, constructor/constructed, finder/found, mind/body, subject/object.\"\nThe second artist which Mackenny writes about is a [[mixed race]] artist who performs a piece called 'Span.' MacKenny asserts that the artist Tracey Rose, alludes to Western societies exploitation of people of colour in scientific study and analysis, and the \"dissection and embalming of body parts of native 'others' (the most pertinent to the South African context being Saartje Baartman, a young Khoisan woman displayed for her unique genitalia and steatopygia, or enlarged buttocks),\" through her own display of her body.<ref name=\"MacKenny\"/> Her performance exposes her naked body and is contrasted against images of \"scientific\" exploitation, which both highlights the dichotomy between these subjects and engages with Mackenny's definition of post-apartheid performance art and its political aim to blur and disrupt binary structures.\n\n=== Anti War Performance Art Movement ===\nThe sociologist Rachel V Kutz-Flamenbaum writes about two major players in the anti-war performance art movement during the George W Bush administration. Code Pink, and Raging Grannies challenge and subvert gender norms in their performances, and thus, use very similar tactics and strategies. For instance, in Code Pink, Kutz-Flamenbaum asserts that, \"the emphasis on women\u2019s role as pacifist caregivers presents a nonthreatening image of women activists.\" \n\nThe perpetuated concept of women as non threatening, relies on the audiences association of pink as a non threatening and feminized colour. Kutz-Flamenbaum argues that \"Code Pink\u2019s use of civil disobedience and aggressive trailing of public officials confound and challenge normative gender expectations of women as passive, polite, and well-behaved.\"(95)<ref name=\"Kutz-Flamenbaum\">{{cite journal|last1=Kutz-Flamenbaum|first1=Rachel V|title=Code Pink, Raging Grannies, and the Missile Dick Chicks: Feminist Performance Activism in the Contemporary Anti-War Movement|journal=NWSA Journal|date=Spring 2001|volume=19|issue=1|pages=90\u201396|issn=1040-0656}}</ref>\nKutz-Flamenbaum claims that [[Raging Grannies]] similarly use this tactic in the description of their mission statement. Kutz-Flamenbaum explains that their mission statement \"illustrates the way Raging Grannies use norm- embracing stereotypes of 'little old ladies' and 'grannies' to challenge the gendered assumptions of their audiences.\" Their conscious performance as non-threatening and nurturing women, strategically and tactfully confront issues related to war and challenge the participation of the George W Bush administration in the war. \n\n== Performance Artists ==\n\n===[[Soad Hosny]]===\n[[File:Suad Husni.jpg|thumb|Suad Husni in 1972 from her movie \"Khalli Balak Min Zoozoo\" (watch out for Zoozoo)]]\n[[Soad Hosny]] (January 26, 1943 \u2013 June 21, 2001)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elfagr.news/2442336|title=\u0634\u0627\u0647\u062f.. \u0634\u0647\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a|website=\u0628\u0648\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u062c\u0631|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> is an Egyptian actress and singer named the \"Cinderella of Egyptian Cinema\".<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://login.colorado.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://bi.gale.com%2fglobal%2farticle%2fGALE%257CA569882059%3fu%3dcoloboulder%26sid%3dsummon|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.colorado.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In her 32 year long career, Hosny preformed in more than [[Soad Hosny filmography|83 films]] and a single TV series called \"Hekayat Hwa we Heya\".<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://https//elcinema.com/en/person/1097577|title=Soad Hosny - Actor Filmography\u060c photos\u060c Video|website=elCinema.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\":03\" />\n\n==== Feminist works ====\n\n===== \"Lilregal Faqat\" =====\nIn 1964, she and [[Nadia Lutfi]] acted in the movie \"Lilregal Faqat\" (For Men Only), which discusses woman's ability to take on jobs that are stereotypically masculine.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allam|first=Nermin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pck-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=feminist+film+%22+lel+regal+fakat%22&source=bl&ots=j-t04-XqFe&sig=ACfU3U34aedePx32Yscd_egNBCUbmDn4og&hl=ar&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj4xZqBuOToAhVYnp4KHburC60Q6AEwAXoECAsQLQ#v=onepage&q=feminist%20film%20%22%20lel%20regal%20fakat%22&f=false|title=Women and the Egyptian Revolution: Engagement and Activism during the 2011 Arab Uprisings|date=2018|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-108-42190-4|language=en}}</ref> In the movie, Soad and Nadia play the roles of two lab workers who report oil-wills locations based on samples they get from the desert. When the male workers in the desert don't find any oil in the locations reported by the two women, they disguise as men and go to the digging-site in the desert.<ref>{{Citation|title=Movie - Lilregal Faqat - 1964 Cast\u060c Video\u060c Trailer\u060c photos\u060c Reviews\u060c Showtimes|url=https://https//elcinema.com/en/work/1001879|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=\u0641\u064a\u0644\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u0631\u062c\u0627\u0644 \u0641\u0642\u0637 {{!}} \u0641\u064a\u0644\u0645 \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a {{!}} \u0628\u0637\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u0649 \u0648 \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hM-FAaGK2zU|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=For Men Only|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0376725/|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n===== \"Hekayat Hwa we Heya\" =====\n\"Hekayat Hwa we Heya\" (The Stories of Him and Her) is a 1985 TV series that revolves around the relationships between the two genders and gender equality.<ref name=\":03\" /><ref name=\":12\" /> In the episode titled \"Garas el Fusha\", Soad perforemed one of her most popular songs, \"elbanat elbanat \" (Girls Girls).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.colorado.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://go.gale.com%2fps%2fi.do%3fp%3dITOF%26u%3dcoloboulder%26id%3dGALE%257CA517578690%26v%3d2.1%26it%3dr%26sid%3dITOF%26asid%3d31a8495c|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.colorado.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> This kids' song raised the equality slogan with phrases like \"Girls are like boys\" and \"we are happy to be born girls\", as it praised girls emphasising that they are smart, talented, strong, wise, beautiful, and kind...etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genderiyya.xyz/wiki/\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a_\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a|title=\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=\u0647\u0648 \u0648\u0647\u064a: \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a .. \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a .. \u0644\u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RDKP_x9dn0w|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Other ====\nIn addition to her direct call for women's rights in some of her works, the Egyptian Cinderella's feminine lively personality, youthful soul, and kind heart encouraged girls to idolise her and gain pride in their gender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.colorado.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://bi.gale.com%2fglobal%2farticle%2fGALE%257CA543828738%3fu%3dcoloboulder%26sid%3dsummon|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.colorado.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2006, [[Mona Zaki]] played the role of Soad Hosny in the biography TV series Named \"Cinderella\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Series - Cinderella - 2006 Cast\u060c Video\u060c Trailer\u060c photos\u060c Reviews\u060c Showtimes|url=https://https//elcinema.com/en/work/1696997|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Commenting on it in one of her interviews, Mona Zaki said that she was a tomboyish kid, and was shy of her feminine features at her early teens, but playing the role of Soad Hosny triggered her pride in being a woman, as it was a turning point in her feelings towards her femininity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynewsarabia.com/varieties/524383-%D9%85%D9%86%D9%89-%D8%B2%D9%83%D9%8A-%D8%B3%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%86%D9%8A-%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B1|title=\u0645\u0646\u0649 \u0632\u0643\u064a: \u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a \u0644\u0645 \u062a\u0646\u062a\u062d\u0631|website=\u0633\u0643\u0627\u064a \u0646\u064a\u0648\u0632 \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><br />\n== [[Frida Kahlo]] ==\nFrida Kahlo's work as an artist remained relatively unknown until the late 1970s to most people outside of Mexico and Latin America, when her work was rediscovered by art historians and political activists she, her art, and her role as a performance artist was brought to the forefront of the art world. In the early 1990s, Kahlo had become a recognized figure in art history, but also regarded as an icon for [[Chicano Movement|Chicana/os]], the [[Latinx]]<nowiki/>community, the [[feminism]]<nowiki/>movement, and the [[LGBTQ+]]<nowiki/>movement. Kahlo's work is celebrated internationally as emblematic of Mexican nationalism and [[Indigenous peoples of Mexico|indigenous]]<nowiki/>traditions and by feminists for what is seen as its uncompromising depiction of the female experience and form.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Broude|first=Norma|url=http://archive.org/details/expandingdiscour00norm|title=The Expanding discourse : feminism and art history|last2=Garrard|first2=Mary D.|date=1992|publisher=New York, NY : IconEditions|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> While she is definitely Mexican, Kahlo is regarded as an icon for Chicana/os who recognize themselves as the hyphen in the middle of the label of Mexican - American. Her depictions of being a person limited by her realities are expressed in her surreal style, which appeal to a broad audience of people from many walks of life.\n\nAlthough [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]], a [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] artist, regarded her primarily as a 'feminista' within the Surrealist movement, Kahlo brought postcolonial issues to the forefront of her brand of Surrealism<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418093138/https://repository.asu.edu/attachments/107983/content/JSA_VOL5_NO1_Pages33-54_Mahon.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2018-04-18|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. Her understanding and visions of being, living with the disabilities she suffered from a trolley accident in her younger years resonate with those also afflicted with disabilities. Her portrayal of herself as a person of color, living the realities of a person limited by her gender, disabilities and a dissident politico made her appealing to an audience previously absent to the art scene. Her art raised the questions of identity. What was it to be a Mexican? \u2013 modern, yet pre-Columbian; young, yet old; anti-Catholic yet Catholic; Western, yet New World; developing, yet underdeveloped; independent, yet colonized; ''mestizo'', yet not Spanish nor Indian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809095503/https://www.gen2.ca/DBHS/Art/3346753.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|last=Bakewell 1993, pg. 169|first=|date=2017-08-09|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n[[File:Las Dos Fridas.jpg|thumb|The Two Fridas, 1939]]\nOriana Baddeley has written that Kahlo has become a signifier of non-conformity and \"the archetype of a cultural minority,\" who is regarded simultaneously as \"a victim, crippled and abused\" and as \"a survivor who fights back.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baddeley|first=St. Clair|date=1897-01-16|title=Waterspout and Whirlwind|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/nq/s8-xi.264.47a|journal=Notes and Queries|volume=s8-XI|issue=264|pages=47\u201347|doi=10.1093/nq/s8-xi.264.47a|issn=1471-6941}}</ref> Edward Sullivan stated that Kahlo is hailed as a hero by so many because she is \"someone to validate their own struggle to find their own voice and their own public personalities\".<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2004|editor-last=Kauffman|editor-first=Kyle D.|editor2-last=Lindauer|editor2-first=David L.|title=AIDS and South Africa|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1057/9780230523517|doi=10.1057/9780230523517}}</ref> According to [[John Berger]], Kahlo's popularity is partly due to the fact that \"the sharing of pain is one of the essential preconditions for a refinding of dignity and hope\" in twenty-first century society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brock\u2010Servais|first=Rhonda|date=2001|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1023/a:1010417217654|journal=Children's Literature in Education|volume=32|issue=3|pages=155\u2013165|doi=10.1023/a:1010417217654|issn=0045-6713}}</ref> She did not use them only to show her subjective experience but to raise questions about Mexican society and the construction of identity within it, particularly gender, race, and social class.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809095503/https://www.gen2.ca/DBHS/Art/3346753.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|last=Bakewell 1993 pg. 168-170|first=|date=2017-08-09|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Frida has become almost saint like to many and a symbol, a feeling to people who like her, have experienced questioning their identity, their place in a society that does not accept difference readily. Her paintings evoke a sense pride in being of Mexican heritage for many and an acceptance for those who have struggled in life.   \n\n\n==[[Yoko Ono]]==\n\n=== Overview ===\nOno belonged to a generation of early feminist performance artists but is unique among them for her international fame as [[John Lennon]]\u2019s wife in the late 60s and 70s.  During their courtship the couple manipulated the press attention directed on them by documenting their relationship through performance art.<ref name=\":0\">Elizabeth Ann Lindau. \u201cMother Superior\u201d: Maternity and Creativity in the Work of Yoko Ono.\" ''Women and Music: A Journal of Gender and Culture'' 20 (University of Nebraska Press: 2016), 64.</ref> As Ono stated in a 1986 TV interview, \u201cwe were always together\u2026 we exchanged very fully between ourselves.\u201d<ref name=\":1\">''Yoko Ono on John Lennon's Assasination, Their Son Sean and Influencing The Beatles Breakup.'', ''YouTube'' (YouTube, 2017), <nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Suj8MCysBKQ</nowiki>)</ref> They emphasized this unusual situation, where the husband and wife worked together rather than the pair working separately outside the home, through their performance art \u201cBed-ins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs an interracial couple they also challenged racial stereotypes. She confessed, \u201cI think it was a big lesson for the world that we were together\u2026 And I think it might have helped too for people to understand what it means to confront the interracial couple.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nParenthood is a factor in the controversy surrounding Ono. Women were not usually part of performance art or rock music, and mothers in particular were antithetical to everything rock stood for. The public idea of rock music as youthful male rebellion placed mothers as the opponent. When Ono and Lennon began their relationship, Beatles fans saw this female influence as an intrusion and the force that broke up their favorite band. However, as Ono saw it, the [[The Beatles|Beatles]] grew apart naturally and she was not the primary cause.<ref name=\":1\" /> Public confusion was exacerbated with Ono\u2019s pregnancy. While pregnant with their son Sean, Ono announced to Lennon: \u201cI am carrying the baby nine months and that is enough. You take care of it afterwards.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> After Sean\u2019s birth, she ran the couple\u2019s business while Lennon stayed home as \u201chousehusband.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Ono\u2019s hands off approach to parenting is a source of controversy because she was simultaneously too motherly and not motherly enough.\n\n=== Work ===\nOne of her early works is [[Cut Piece]], first performed in 1964 at the Yamaichi Concert Hall in Kyoto. She kneeled on the stage in her best suit and invited audience members to use scissors to cut it off of her. Confronting issues of gender, class and cultural identity, Ono sat silently until the piece concluded at her discretion.<ref>Munroe, Alexandra; Ono, Yoko; Hendricks, Jon; Altshuler, Bruce; Ross, David A.; Wenner, Jann S.; Concannon, Kevin C.; Tomii, Reiko; Sayle, Murray; Gomez, Edward M. (October 2000). Yes Yoko Ono. New York: Harry N. Abrams. {{ISBN|0-81094-587-8}}.</ref> Ono also published a book of conceptual art in 1964, entitled [[Grapefruit (book)|Grapefruit]]. The book reads like an instruction manual for the reader to create their own versions of her pieces either physically or in the imagination. Over the nearly 60 years that she has been active, Ono has created installations of modern art across the globe, recorded numerous original songs both with John Lennon and the [[Plastic Ono Band]], as well as individually, and continues in activism to this day.\n\n== Orlan==\nORLAN (born as Mireille Suzanne Francette Porte) is French performance artist, most known for her radical use of plastic surgery to form her work. She uses her face and body as a malleable tool to change her appearance and therefore change her art. She primarily used plastic surgery to morph and change her body in her theatrical expression. Orlan uses her body at the heart of her expression, to articulate her political, social and cultural beliefs. Due to suffering an ectopic pregnancy, she felt her body was changed dramatically, and through that, she chose to turn her body into artwork through the use of plastic surgery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/orlan/|title=ORLAN {{!}} artnet|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOne of her most notable performances was that of the 1977 International Contemporary Art Fair in Paris. On her exterior, she had a large photo of a torso on her chest. This was turned into a slot machine, where the audience could put a coin down the slot and watch it descend into the groin. As a reward, that audience member were given a kiss. She also displayed her sexual organs during menstruation under a magnifying glass for respective audience members to study. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Donger|first=Simon|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XoXFBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=orlan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyw_Da7snoAhVxlFwKHZmmAdsQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=orlan&f=false|title=ORLAN: A Hybrid Body of Artworks|last2=Shepherd|first2=Simon|date=2010-05-20|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-97128-0|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Bj\u00f6rk Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir ==\nThe musical artist Bj\u00f6rk has been challenging musical barriers since her time in the band [[The Sugarcubes]], which became the biggest alternative rock band in Iceland. She has since gone on to a solo career, starting in 1993 with the album [[Debut (Bj\u00f6rk album)|''Debut'']] with her last album having been released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bj%C3%B6rk-mn0000769444/biography|title=Bj\u00f6rk {{!}} Biography & History|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> She throughout her time has used her music to speak on matters she deemed important while following a unique and individualistic style for each of her albums. She finds something that she finds challenging or that she dislikes and work with it to create something she's proud of, allowing her to continue having these unique albums.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4143741-interview--bjork-talks-piracy-punk-lady-gaga-and-biophilia|title=Interview: Bjork talks piracy, punk, Lady Gaga and Biophilia|last=October 9th|first=Kevin EG Perry|last2=2011|website=DrownedInSound|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== ''Biophilia and Environmental Work'' ===\nThis has lead to one of her most famous albums ''[[Biophilia (album)|Biophilia]]'' which was Bj\u00f6rk's two year long passion project to give her music a more visual and hands on feel. The album was developed into an iPad and iPod app that allowed users to listen to each song while playing games that visually showcased the music. The most notable example is the song \u2018Thunderbolt\u2019  which allows listeners to draw \"Tesla coil charges which alter the bass lines you hear\" and when she performs the song live she has twin Tesla coils to play the bass line.<ref name=\":2\" /> This album however was more than a challenge for Bj\u00f6rk to create a new sound, she created the album as a response to the environmental issues Iceland was facing in 2008. Iceland had allowed the aluminum smelters to take over the countries fishing industry while being the cause for excessive greenhouse gas emissions. Her goal was to create an album that could educate people about the world we are living in and inspire them to take actions against companies that work to destroy the planet.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/07/bjork-environmental-campaign-timetable-nordic-schools|title=Bj\u00f6rk's environmental campaign goes on the timetable in Nordic schools|date=2014-06-07|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=arts|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|last3=correspondent|first3=media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/11/13/bjork-wages-battle-against-icelandic-aluminum/|title=Bj\u00f6rk Wages Battle Against Icelandic Aluminum|last=Kanter|first=James|date=2008-11-13|website=Green Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== 'Declare Independence' and Activism ===\nThis environmental work would not be the only time she has used her music and voice to speak out as the song 'Declare Independence' would often be a song she would use to speak out for the freedom of nations trying to seceded from the nations they have been forced to be apart of. Most notable was when she, unauthorized, sang the song in her Shanghai concert in 2008, chanting Tibet in the middle of the song.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7276891.stm|title=Bjork makes 'free Tibet' gesture|date=2008-03-04|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> At the time Tibet was revolting against China for its freedom, and as such her use of the song caused many concert goers to leave the venue and the Chinese government to tighten their regulations for all outside performers from then on. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7293605.stm|title=Western acts 'welcome' in China|date=2008-03-13|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Lady Gaga ==\nLady Gaga (Stefani Joanne Angelina Germanotta) has experimented and incorporated performance art into her life. Her first internet appearance in performance art came in 2013 in a kickstarter for \u201cThe Abromovic Method\u201d ran by Marina Abromovic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/71937056|title=The Abramovic Method Practiced by Lady Gaga|website=Vimeo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>This video was taken during a physical and spiritual retreat she participated that was hosted by Abromovic at her summer home. Gaga is featured \u201cfilling the room\u201d with her voice and wandering naked in the woods. Gaga was asked to test her body and go through strenuous activities. She also added to the piece by participating fully and even suggesting additions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://culturacolectiva.com/art/lady-gaga-marina-abramovic-collaboration|title=The Day Lady Gaga Stripped To Please Marina Abramovic and Be Free From Drugs|date=2017-01-30|website=culturacolectiva.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Abbromovic reported she was a very compliant student. Later, Gaga fit performance art into her 2011 Video Music Awards appearance. She showed up to perform her song \u201cYou and I\u201d dressed up as a person deemed Jo Calderone. <ref>{{Citation|title=Jo Calderone (Lady Gaga) You And I Live - VMAs 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SkWoA25V4tQ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> When speaking, she spoke with a Brooklyn accent and walk, and spoke as a typical man. She commented that performance art meant fully committing and diving into a character including, acting as the character the whole night. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1669957/lady-gaga-jo-calderone-vmas/|title=Why Did Lady Gaga Go To VMAs As Jo Calderone?|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>They finished their speech at the award show talking about the importance of accepting people for who they are with no discrimination, because it was they way they were born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-339-1286022|title=Lady Gaga performs as male alter ego Jo Calderone at MTV VMAs {{!}} NME|date=2011-08-29|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Later Gaga dabbled with the performance art of \u201cCamp\u201d at the 2019 Met Gala. \"Camp\" is a form of performance art through clothing that stems from the drag culture and is meant to tell a story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://depauliaonline.com/41447/artslife/camp-the-theme-that-means-the-most-or-nothing-at-all/|title=Camp: the theme that means the most \u2013 or nothing at all|last=Oxnevad|first=Emma|date=2019-05-13|website=The DePaulia|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance through clothing ====\nHer outfit for the Met Gala consisted of four overlapping outfits that she stripped from one to the next while on the red carpet for the Gala.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peters|first=Micheal A|date=January 2012|title=On the Edge of Theory: Lady Gaga, performance and cultural theory|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwVV3NCsIwDC6yg7_vEPAkOLGuW1tvIv6B4EW9jmzddlNxevDtTdyGeuolCaVNkyZNvnaFR3Fr1hKdmYy48yOcefywq_hcBbrd5D8YZ0YF045YHC5Adx3g9BFcc_g08L3msEf3gg0WOIbbt4YeKL6GBpSipu0L73F_ZoNq6InTenVcbv36MwG_YFAqPzQJ6Sqiy6RLlMxDY8n1WtQBzVBl1jolU0PeNpeJY5ASIjaJZguvXW74Y91hJbcx2XG92-UHZNNMtY0YfHBSUbF9j1lJHndMsa51p4VhuKV4wWIVO1NiGP0xcIU6meUCn2UZ7w7nX9o339xjrg|journal=Contemporary readings in Law and social Justice|volume=4|pages=1|via=}}</ref> The outfits consisted of black and pink and had a coy, classic femme aesthetic.She also had a team providing her with props like a suitcase, wagon and 90\u2019s telephone. She also represented performance art on a mainstream platform with two separate VMA appearances. One was in 2010, when she wore a \u201cmeat dress\u201d to the show. The dress consisted of prime rib and flank steak. The dress was referencing a speech \u201cThe Prime Rib of America\u201d, that encouraged the end of discrimination against gay men and women in the military and Gaga stated the military denies them \u201c the greatest cut of meat my country has to offer.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/lady-gaga-meat-dress-explanation|title=Getting Political|website=British Vogue|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The second was the Joe Calerone one previously mentioned, both performed with intent of raising awareness to a cause.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kumari|first=Ashanka|date=April 2016|title=\"You and I\"|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMw42JgAfZbUxkgJ4GCF80UJJfqAasRA1Mm0NmlJga6ppbGwDwEPcUb2MPggBWdwNaEASdDwKOGOZH5h_coAPvSCp6PGuZaKUB3rVaChYAtI4UAxLJ6hfw0heDUnDSFzDwFn8SUSgX3xPREsELwJpDkwyt5GFhKikpTeSEUN0Oom2uIs4cu9LYBXVCVZ6prngwszFMNLcyTjdIsDI2TzE2SUlIsLU2NUkySk43NTYEJNTHVJDUl0SQ5CbQdNBlYV6aapYAyhWliYhro4nUtiLmw-i2-AHJgRDy8oQ0MiXhwSAAVq0IVo0x2xyeCphvig4ANKVDWAF2iZAhRB2454zEx3ivAORRiNgDmtXCK|journal=The Journal of Pop Culture|volume=49|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance of her own feminism ====\nShe preaches about equality to all through the removing of labels and just treating people as people. Her main message is to spread kindness over all else.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jennex|first=Craig|date=July 2013|title=Diva Worship and the Sonic Search for Queer Utopia|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwfV09DwIhDCXmBj__A4sjBo7qweTgR1z9uDgSUEicNOb090vhjLo4sRRIF9pH2_f6pIi41ZN2Sg1prGXijMF-ACEnlVZTgE4aU-RMVKIs0j8_Z2jT_TyiHHqkXF6elh6vqaOXRmhNY1ZE90gaS3M7Lo2pHd1GzHendXO9XeyQFM394Ud5GZB6vTosNqxVFmAnyRWwADNnBaCanXBVlVjDtJKOSzs7O-twHFW7ABq8kFaBdlB6OPMgrPcyoMg65HPfsczcMjmEEW_OzdZrg16b7HXcNm63_ZS4jcUig9nFbD3Gb4V282z3zZ5qmoThQxbcMPLvTS-VRmpL|journal=Popular Music and Society: Fandom|volume=36|pages=3|via=}}</ref> She believes women have the right to choose the life they see fit for themselves, even if it means dependent on others. She is also a big advocate for sexual assault awareness as she is a survivor herself. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Corona|first=Victor P.|date=2013|title=Memory, Monsters, and Lady Gaga|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|journal=The Journal of Popular Culture|language=en|volume=46|issue=4|pages=725\u2013744|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|issn=1540-5931}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== The Guerrilla Girls ==\nThe Guerrilla Girls formed in New York City in the mid 1980s.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/guerrilla-girls-6858|title=Guerrilla Girls|last=Tate|website=Tate|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>The Guerrilla Girls focused their performances, protests, installations, and exhibits on highlighting the lack of representation of women and people of color within the art world.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> Most notably, The Guerrilla Girls donned gorilla masks and costumes during protest in order to maintain anonymity, and to make their work more about the issues rather than each member\u2019s own identity.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nAfter protesting the lack of diversity at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City in 1985, the Guerrilla Girls expanded their work into prints, billboards, public commissions, and, indoor exhibitions. This also came with their work focusing on a wider array of issues such as the wage gap, tokenism, and funding for the arts.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> The public performances of the Guerrilla Girls in the early days took the form of protest, by wearing their gorilla masks and conducting \"weenie counts\" in museums, where the members would count he male to female work and subject ratios. Most notably in 1989 they found that The Met's public collections only had 5% of their works produced by women, while 85% of the works including nudity focused on a nude female. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref>\n\nThe Guerrilla Girls have been met with criticism and backlash. While they focus on the issue of diversity, it has been said that the majority of the members are white. Former member, Alma Thomas have noted the lack of effort in understanding the challenges faced by artists of color by other members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-guerrilla-girls-zora-neale-hurston-and-agnes-martin-15840|title=Oral history interview with Guerrilla Girls Zora Neale Hurston and Agnes Martin, 2008 May 17|website=www.aaa.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The Guerrilla Girls have also been accused of \u201cselling out,\u201d having their works shown at the same hegemonic establishments that they protested in the past.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/guerrilla-girl-power-have-americas-feminist-artists-sold-out-1666140.html|title=Guerrilla girl power: Have America's feminist artists sold out?|date=2009-04-09|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== [[Ana Mendieta]] ==\n\n=== Overview ===\nMendieta's work was greatly informed by the part of her identity that was embedded in the term \"immigrant\". She's widely known for her performance art and art book full of her pieces called ''Traces''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-in-america/interviews/the-untold-ana-mendieta-56344/|title=The Untold: Ana Mendieta|last=Donnelly|first=Ryann|last2=Donnelly|first2=Ryann|date=2013-10-08|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>''.'' Her immigration from Cuba to the USA was full of displacement and separation from her homeland and many of her family members for a long period of time. This inspired her future work to explore the aspects of belonging, estrangement, feminism, life, death, violence and overall the rawness of the natural of femininity and the earth. Her fascinations with natures elements: water, fire, earth, air and the flesh were interwoven into her performance art work. She was a huge part of the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/body-art/ body art movement] which was it's own form that grew as a branch off from the trunk of performance art<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theartstory.org/artist/mendieta-ana/|title=Ana Mendieta Art, Bio, Ideas|website=The Art Story|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Furthermore, she was seen as a huge contributor to the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/earth-art/ land art movement] which she often paired with her body art to create her feminist and identity messages in her performance art pieces<ref name=\":3\" />. Her untimely death at 36 years old left audiences hurting for more, but some of her pieces still stand in art studios today such as [[Alison Jacques Gallery]] and are incorporated in conversations about feminist and immigrant artwork<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alisonjacquesgallery.com/exhibitions/|title=Gallery Programme|website=Alison Jacques Gallery|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>.<br />    \n\n== Gesel Mason ==\nGesel Mason is choreographer, educator, performer, and arts facilitator. Currently, she is the Artistic Director of Gesel Mason Performance Projects and an Associate Professor at the University of Texas at Austin. Gesel has performed for and been a member of numerous well-established choreographers and companies. In her work, Mason utilizes dance, theater, humor, and storytelling to bring visibility to those voices unheard, situation neglected, or perspectives considered taboo.(Cite). Mason has cultivated a multitude of works and performances including her highlighted projects; Women, Desire, & Sex, antithesis, and No Boundaries.\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Feminist art]]\n", "name_user": "Tyyy13", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feminist_performance_art"}
{"title_page": "Tom Hardy", "text_new": "{{for|other people named Tom Hardy|Thomas Hardy (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|English actor, screenwriter, and producer}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tom Hardy\n| honorific_suffix   = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}}\n| image              = Tom Hardy by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Hardy at the 2018 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] promoting ''[[Venom (2018 film)|Venom]]''\n| birth_name         = Edward Thomas Hardy\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1977|09|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n<!--| residence          = [[Richmond, London]], England-->| occupation         = {{Hlist|Actor|producer|model}}\n| yearsactive        = 1998\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{marriage|Sarah Ward|1999|2004}}|{{marriage|[[Charlotte Riley]]|July 2014}}}}\n| children           = 3\n| parents            = [[Chips Hardy]] (father)\n}}\n\n'''Edward Thomas Hardy''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (born 15 September 1977) is an English actor and producer. After studying acting at the [[Drama Centre London]], he made his film debut in [[Ridley Scott]]'s ''[[Black Hawk Down (film)|Black Hawk Down]]'' (2001) and has since appeared in such films as ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis]]'' (2002), ''[[RocknRolla]]'' (2008), ''[[Bronson (film)|Bronson]]'' (2008), ''[[Warrior (2011 film)|Warrior]]'' (2011), ''[[Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy (film)|Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy]]'' (2011), ''[[Lawless (film)|Lawless]]'' (2012), ''[[Locke (film)|Locke]]'' (2013), ''[[The Drop (film)|The Drop]]'' (2014), and ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'' (2015), for which he received a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. In 2015, Hardy portrayed [[Max Rockatansky|\"Mad\" Max Rockatansky]] in ''[[Mad Max: Fury Road]]'' and both [[Kray twins]] in ''[[Legend (2015 film)|Legend]]''. He has appeared in three [[Christopher Nolan]] films: ''[[Inception]]'' (2010), ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012) as [[Bane (DC Comics)|Bane]], and ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017) as an [[RAF]] fighter-pilot. He starred as [[Eddie Brock]] / [[Venom (Marvel Comics character)|Venom]] in the 2018 anti-hero film ''[[Venom (2018 film)|Venom]]''.\n\nHardy's television roles include the [[HBO]] war drama mini-series ''[[Band of Brothers (miniseries)|Band of Brothers]]'' (2001), the [[BBC]] historical drama mini-series ''[[The Virgin Queen (TV serial)|The Virgin Queen]]'' (2005), [[Bill Sikes]] in the BBC's mini-series ''[[Oliver Twist (2007 TV miniseries)|Oliver Twist]]'' (2007), [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[Wuthering Heights (2009 TV serial)|Wuthering Heights]]'' (2008), the [[Sky 1]] drama series ''[[The Take (TV series)|The Take]]'' (2009), and the BBC historical crime drama series ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'' (2013\u2013). He created, co-produced, and took the lead in the eight-part [[historical fiction]] series ''[[Taboo (2017 TV series)|Taboo]]'' (2017) on [[BBC One]] and [[FX (TV channel)|FX]].<ref name=\"Taboo2017\">{{cite news|last=Swift|first1=Andy|title=Tom Hardy's FX/BBC One Drama Taboo Adds 13, Begins Production|url=http://tvline.com/2015/11/23/tom-hardy-taboo-fx-drama-cast-game-of-thrones-actors/|accessdate=16 January 2017|publisher=tvline.com|date=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHardy has performed on both British and American stages. He was nominated for the [[Laurence Olivier Awards|Laurence Olivier Award]] for Most Promising Newcomer for his role as Skank in the production of ''[[In Arabia We'd All Be Kings]]'' (2003), and was awarded the 2003 [[Evening Standard Awards|''Evening Standard'' Theatre Award]] for Outstanding Newcomer for his performances in both ''In Arabia We'd All Be Kings'' and for his role as Luca in ''Blood''. He starred in the production of ''[[The Man of Mode]]'' (2007) and received positive reviews for his role in the play ''The Long Red Road'' (2010).\n\nHardy is active in charity work and is an ambassador for the [[Prince's Trust]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Young |first1=Niki May |title=Celebrity patron Tom Hardy helps save homelessness charity from closure |url=https://www.civilsociety.co.uk/news/celebrity-patron-tom-hardy-helps-save-homelessness-charity-from-closure.html |accessdate=16 June 2018 |work=Civil Society |date=20 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=For Tom Hardy, Adoption Is the Only Option |url=https://www.peta.org/features/tom-hardy-dog-adoption-ad/ |accessdate=16 June 2018 |work=PETA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=British Stars Take A Run At Beating Cancer |url=https://news.sky.com/story/british-stars-take-a-run-at-beating-cancer-10390500 |accessdate=16 June 2018 |work=[[Sky News]] |date=8 September 2014}}</ref> He was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2018 Birthday Honours]] for services to drama.<ref name=\"honours\">{{cite news |title=Dalglish and Thompson head honours list |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-44397682 |accessdate=16 June 2018 |work=BBC News |date=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=From rehab to royal honour: Tom Hardy is made a CBE |url=https://www.irishnews.com/magazine/entertainment/2018/06/08/news/from-rehab-to-royal-honour-tom-hardy-is-made-a-cbe-1352123/ |accessdate=16 June 2018 |work=[[The Irish News]] |date=8 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nEdward Thomas Hardy<ref>{{cite news|last=Hadfield |first=Tom |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/active/8722690/Tom-Hardy-timeline.html |title=Tom Hardy timeline |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=25 August 2011 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> was born on 15 September 1977<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/celebrity/biographies/tom-hardy|title=Tom Hardy biography - Celebrity A-Zs GLAMOUR.com|publisher=Glamour.com UK|accessdate=30 June 2013}}</ref> in [[Hammersmith]], [[London]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Grainger |first=Lisa |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/ultratravel/9889047/Tom-Hardys-Travelling-Life.html |title=Tom Hardy's Travelling Life |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 April 2013 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> the only child of artist and [[painter]] Anne (''n\u00e9e'' Barrett) and novelist and [[comedy writer]] [[Chips Hardy|Edward \"Chips\" Hardy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/feat/archives/2010/07/07/2003477285/3 |title=From misfit to Mad Max |work=[[Taipei Times]] |date=9 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5846093.ece | location=London | work=The Times | title=A tough life for Bronson actor Tom Hardy | first=Kevin | last=Maher | date=5 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/jul/04/tom-hardy-actor-film-inception | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Tom Hardy: the rake's progress | first=Alice | last=Fisher | date=4 July 2010}}</ref> His mother is of  [[Irish people|Irish]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|title=The U.K. movie star and the Vancouver tattoo artist he can't get enough of|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/the-uk-movie-star-and-the-vancouver-tattoo-artist-he-cant-get-enough-of/article1316029/|accessdate=20 June 2015|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=23 August 2012}}</ref> Hardy was brought up in [[East Sheen|East Sheen, London]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2002/12/09/an-interview-with-tom-hardy | publisher=IGN | title=An Interview with Tom Hardy | first=Steve| last=Head |accessdate=4 June 2011 |date=9 December 2002}}</ref> He studied at [[Tower House School]], [[Reed's School]], and Duff Miller Sixth Form College. He later studied at [[Richmond Adult Community College|Richmond Drama School]] and the [[Drama Centre London]], a part of [[Central Saint Martins]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Hardy Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/tom-hardy-21369405#synopsis|publisher=[[Biography.com]]|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tom Hardy: Real-life blows that shaped my acting|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/8723292/Tom-Hardy-interview-Real-life-blows-that-shaped-my-acting.html |accessdate=31 December 2018 |agency=The Telegraph}}</ref> He has named [[Gary Oldman]] as his \"hero\", adding that he mirrored scenes from the actor while at drama school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/films/meet-tom-hardy|title=Meet Tom Hardy|last=Dickens|first=Andrew|website=[[ShortList]]|access-date=23 February 2017|date=2011-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/interviews/a340536/tinker-tailor-soldier-spy-tom-hardy-video-interview-gary-oldman-is-my-hero/|title='Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy' Tom Hardy video interview: 'Gary Oldman is my hero'|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|date=16 September 2011|work=[[Digital Spy]]|access-date=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1998\u20132010===\n\nIn 1998, Hardy won ''[[The Big Breakfast]]''{{'s}} ''Find Me a Supermodel'' competition at age 21 (and with it a brief contract with Models One).<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Hardy wins modeling contest in 1998|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2012/08/23/tom-hardy-modeling-contest-gary-oldman|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=23 August 2012}}</ref> Hardy joined [[Drama Centre London]] in September 1998, and was taken out early after winning the part of US Army Private John Janovec in the award-winning [[HBO]]-BBC [[mini-series]] ''[[Band of Brothers (miniseries)|Band of Brothers]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Way Back When: Tom Hardy|url=https://screencrush.com/way-back-when-tom-hardy/|accessdate=25 June 2015|publisher=screencrush.com|date=8 November 2012}}</ref> He made his feature film debut in [[Ridley Scott]]'s war thriller ''[[Black Hawk Down (film)|Black Hawk Down]]'' (2001).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Strange roles of Tom Hardy|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/features/the-strange-roles-of-tom-hardy.php|publisher=/filmschoolrejects.com|accessdate=25 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512143255/http://filmschoolrejects.com/features/the-strange-roles-of-tom-hardy.php|archivedate=12 May 2015}}</ref> During this time, Hardy also had a brief stint as a rapper and hip hop producer with his friend Edward Tracy (under the name \"Tommy No 1 + Eddie Too Tall\"), with whom he recorded a mixtape called ''Falling On Your Arse In 1999'' that remained unreleased until 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/59wa3d/tom-hardys-rap-mixtape-from-1999-is-actually-kind-of-fire |title=Tom Hardy's Rap Mixtape from 1999 Is Actually Kind of Fire - Noisey |work=Noisey.vice.com |date=19 January 2018 |accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Hardy gained considerable international exposure as the [[Romulan Home Worlds|Reman]] [[Praetor]] [[Shinzon]], a [[cloning|clone]] of [[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701-E)|USS ''Enterprise'']] Captain [[Jean-Luc Picard]] in ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Is Tom Hardy's 'Star Trek: Nemesis' screen test better than the finished film? -|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2012/07/30/is-tom-hardys-star-trek-nemesis-screen-test-better-than-the-finished-film-video|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=30 July 2012}}</ref> The following year, he appeared in the film ''[[Dot the i]]'', and then travelled to North Africa for ''Simon: An English Legionnaire'', a story of the [[French Foreign Legion]]. He then returned to the United Kingdom to feature in the horror film ''[[LD 50 Lethal Dose]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite news|title=An interview with Tom Hardy|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2002/12/09/an-interview-with-tom-hardy|accessdate=25 June 2015|publisher=ign.com|date=9 December 2002}}</ref>\n[[File:TomHardyJuly10 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Hardy at the London premiere of ''[[Inception]]'' in 2010]]\nHardy was awarded the 2003 [[Evening Standard Awards|London Evening Standard Theatre Award]] for Outstanding Newcomer for his performances in ''Blood'' and ''[[In Arabia We'd All Be Kings]]'' performed at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] and [[Hampstead Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Evening Standard Theatre Awards: the rise of eight Outstanding Newcomers|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/evening-standard-theatre-awards-the-rise-of-eight-outstanding-newcomers-9931578.html|accessdate=25 June 2015|publisher=Standard|date=17 December 2014}}</ref> He was also nominated for a 2004 [[Laurence Olivier Awards|Laurence Olivier Award]] for Most Promising Newcomer of 2003 in a Society of London Theatre Affiliate for his performance as Skank in the aforementioned production of ''In Arabia We'd All Be Kings''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Olivier Awards 2004|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/winners/view/item98547/olivier-winners-2004/|publisher=olivierawards.com|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> Hardy appeared with [[Emilia Fox]] in the BBC mini-series ''[[The Virgin Queen (TV serial)|The Virgin Queen]]'' (2005) as [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert Dudley]], a childhood friend of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]]. Dudley's character has been described as an ambiguous young man who is torn between the affection of his wife (played by Fox), his love for Elizabeth and his own ambitions.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Virgin Queen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/virginqueen/tom_hardy.shtml|publisher=BBC|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> Hardy featured in the [[BBC Four]] adaptation of the 1960s [[science fiction]] series ''[[A for Andromeda (2006 film)|A for Andromeda]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=A for Andromeda|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0074sc9|publisher=BBC|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he appeared in [[BBC Two]]'s drama based on a true story, ''[[Stuart: A Life Backwards]]''. He played the lead role of Stuart Shorter, a homeless man who had been subjected to years of abuse and whose death was possibly a suicide.<ref>{{cite news|title=The weekend's TV: Stuart: A Life Backwards|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2007/sep/24/theweekendstvstuartalife|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=The Guardian|date=24 September 2007}}</ref> The same year he played [[Bill Sikes]] in the BBC mini-series ''[[Oliver Twist (2007 miniseries)|Oliver Twist]]'', an adaptation of [[Charles Dickens]]\u2019 novel that aired on [[PBS]] ''[[Masterpiece Classic]]'' in the US. In February 2008, he played a drug-addicted [[rape|rapist]] in the British horror-thriller ''[[W\u0394Z]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=WAZ|url=https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=134271|accessdate=25 June 2015|work=Empire}}</ref> In September 2008, he appeared in [[Guy Ritchie]]'s London gangster film, ''[[RocknRolla]]''; Hardy played the role of [[gay]] gangster Handsome Bob.<ref>{{cite news|title=Handsome Devil|url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/2008/10/30/handsome-devil|accessdate=25 June 2015|publisher=/www.out.com|date=30 October 2008}}</ref> Though a sequel to ''RocknRolla'', titled ''The Real RocknRolla'', has been rumoured to be in production, in which Hardy will reprise the role of Handsome Bob, filming has yet to commence on the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guy Ritchie Has Finished \u2018RocknRolla\u2019 Sequel Script; Waiting On Schedule To Shoot|url=http://thefilmstage.com/news/guy-ritche-talks-rocknrolla-sequel/|accessdate=25 June 2015|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> In 2008, Hardy starred in the film ''[[Bronson (film)|Bronson]]'', about the real-life English prisoner [[Charles Bronson (prisoner)|Charles Bronson]], who has spent most of his adult life in [[solitary confinement]]. For the film, he put on three [[Stone (unit)|stone]] (19&nbsp;kg/42 pounds).<ref>{{cite web |title = Actors Who've Gone Big |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Verlagsgruppe|Bauer Consumer Media]] |date = 13 March 2009|url = https://www.empireonline.com/features/buffed-up-actors/default.asp |accessdate =8 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, Hardy starred in [[Martina Cole]]'s four-part TV drama ''[[The Take (TV series)|The Take]]'' on [[Sky One]], as a drug and alcohol-fuelled gangster. The role gained him a Best Actor nomination at the 2009 [[Crime Thriller Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Allen, Kate |date=7 September 2009 |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/96297-coben-cole-atkinson-vie-for-crime-awards.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090910005647/http://www.thebookseller.com/news/96297-coben-cole-atkinson-vie-for-crime-awards.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=10 September 2009 |title=Coben, Cole, Atkinson vie for crime awards |work=The Bookseller |accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> In August 2009, he appeared in [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[Wuthering Heights (2009 TV serial)|Wuthering Heights]]'', playing the role of Heathcliff, the classic love character who falls in love with his childhood friend Cathy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sanborn|first=Victoire|date=16 January 2009|title=Wuthering Heights \"Is Mr. Heathcliff a Man?\"|url=https://www.pbs.org/remotelyconnected/2009/01/wuthering_heights_1.html|accessdate=25 June 2015|publisher=[[pbs.org]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Heathcliff in Wuthering Heights |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/wutheringheights/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122061648/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/wutheringheights/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 January 2009 |publisher=pbs.org |accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> In early 2010, Hardy starred in ''The Long Red Road'' at the [[Goodman Theatre]] in [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/136886-Tom-Hardy-Journeys-Goodmans-Long-Red-Road-a-World-Premiere-Starting-Feb-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215034957/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/136886-Tom-Hardy-Journeys-Goodmans-Long-Red-Road-a-World-Premiere-Starting-Feb-13 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 February 2010 |title=Tom Hardy Journeys Goodman's Long Red Road, a World Premiere, Starting Feb.&nbsp;13 |last=Jones |first=Kenneth |date=13 February 2010 |work=Playbill Web site |accessdate=22 March 2010}}</ref> The play was written by Brett C. Leonard and directed by [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]]. Hardy won some good reviews for his portrayal of Sam, an alcoholic trying to drink away his past.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwitimes.com/entertainment/columnists/offbeat/article_94b1759b-5493-569d-a55a-ef77869b1644.html|title=OFFBEAT: Goodman Theatre's 'The Long Red Road' is brilliant masterpiece|last=Potempa|first=Phillip|date=24 February 2010|publisher=nwi.com|accessdate=22 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newcitystage.com/2010/02/22/review-the-long-red-roadgoodman-theatre/|title=Review: The Long Red Road/Goodman Theatre|last=Hieggelke|first=Brian|date=22 February 2010|work=Newcity Stage|accessdate=22 March 2010}}</ref> In 2010, he starred as Eames in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s science fiction thriller ''[[Inception]]'' for which he won a [[BAFTA]] Rising Star award. Hardy replaced [[Michael Fassbender]] in the [[Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy (film)|2011 film adaptation]] of ''[[Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=69516 |title=Tom Hardy Replaces Fassbender in Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=3 September 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> released on 5 September 2011 at the 68th edition of the [[Venice Film Festival|Mostra Internazionale d'Arte Cinematografica]] in [[Venice]]. In March 2010, Hardy signed a [[first-look deal]] at [[Warner Bros.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118051165 |title=Tom Hardy joins WB's first-look roster |work=Variety |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u2013present===\n[[File:The Drop 34 (15253481792).jpg|thumb|right|Hardy at the premiere of ''[[The Drop (film)|The Drop]]'', 2014 [[Toronto Film Festival]]]]\nIn 2011, Hardy starred in the film ''[[Warrior (2011 film)|Warrior]]'', which was released on 9 September 2011 by [[Lionsgate]] Films. His performance as Tommy Riordan, who is trained by his father to fight in a mixed martial arts tournament against his brother, gained praise from critics. Hardy also starred in ''[[This Means War (film)|This Means War]]'' (2012), a romantic comedy directed by [[McG]]. He played the [[supervillain]] [[Bane (Tom Hardy)|Bane]] in ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'', the final film in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s ''[[The Dark Knight Trilogy]]'', released on 20 July 2012.<ref>Ryan (13 October 2010). He was filming in [[Alvor (Portim\u00e3o)|Alvor]], [[Algarve]], Portugal through the summer of 2011 for this role as well as other locations throughout Europe.[https://web.archive.org/web/20101020150548/http://www.reelzchannel.com/movie-news/7950/tom-hardy-joins-batman-3-cast-fury-road-delayed \"Tom Hardy Joins Batman 3 Cast; Fury Road Delayed\"]. reelzchannel.com.</ref> He played a bootlegger in [[John Hillcoat]]'s crime drama ''[[Lawless (film)|Lawless]]'' (2012).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2010/12/tom-hardy-shia-labeouf-wettest-county.html|title=Shia LaBeouf and Tom Hardy will be bootleggers|first=Steven|last=Zeitchik|work=Los Angeles Times|date=7 December 2010|accessdate=10 February 2011}}</ref> Hardy has signed up to play the lead role of [[Sam Fisher (Splinter Cell)|Sam Fisher]] in [[Ubisoft]]'s forthcoming film adaptation of their video game series ''[[Tom Clancy's Splinter Cell]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Doug Liman To Helm \u2018Splinter Cell\u2019 With Tom Hardy|url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/doug-liman-to-helm-splinter-cell-with-tom-hardy-701602/|accessdate=20 June 2015|publisher=Deadline.com|date=19 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2012/digital/news/tom-hardy-game-for-splinter-cell-movie-1118062220/#|title=Tom Hardy game for 'Splinter Cell' movie|work=Variety|date=14 November 2012|accessdate=8 November 2013|first=Marc|last=Graser}}</ref> He also appeared in [[Riz Ahmed|Riz Mc]]'s music video for the song \"Sour Times\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Riz MC - Sour Times|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EfXvKKflBoM|publisher=youtube|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Hardy starred in the crime film ''[[The Drop (film)|The Drop]]'' alongside [[James Gandolfini]], in what would be the latter's final appearance in a feature film before his death. Hardy also joined the cast of the [[BBC]] crime drama ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'' in its second series. He portrays Alfie Solomons, the head of a Jewish gang and runner of a distillery which disguises itself as a bakery.\n\n[[File:Cannes 2015 43.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|Hardy (right) with [[George Miller (director)|George Miller]] and [[Charlize Theron]] at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nHardy starred in five films in 2015. The first, ''[[Child 44 (film)|Child 44]]'', set in 1950s [[Soviet Union]], saw him playing Leo Demidov, a Soviet secret police agent who investigates a series of child murders. Despite mild praise for his acting, ''Child 44'' was reviewed negatively by critics and was a box office failure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/22/global-box-office-child-44-furious-7-paul-blart-mall-cop-2|title=How is Tom Hardy's $50m Child 44 such a totalitarian fail?|last=Hoad|first=Phil|date=22 April 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref> Hardy then played the title character, [[Max Rockatansky]], in the action film ''[[Mad Max: Fury Road]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/05/25/high-gear-current-cinema-anthony-lane|title=\"Mad Max: Fury Road\" Review|date=25 May 2015|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Rosenberg|first=Adam|title=Tom Hardy landing the starring role in \"Mad Max: Fury Road\" is an amazing turn of events for that franchise.|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2009/12/01/exclusive-mad-max-speaks-bronson-star-tom-hardy-on-his-coming-game-changer/|publisher=MTV|accessdate=3 March 2011}}</ref> His performance was praised by critics<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Hardy gives new life to 'Mad Max'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/05/14/tom-hardy-gives-new-life-to-mad-max-fury-road/27135973/|accessdate=16 July 2015|work=USA Today|date=14 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Review: 'Mad Max: Fury Road' an 'out-of-control reboot' |url=http://canadaam.ctvnews.ca/movie-reviews/review-mad-max-fury-road-an-out-of-control-reboot-1.2373935 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518020039/http://canadaam.ctvnews.ca/movie-reviews/review-mad-max-fury-road-an-out-of-control-reboot-1.2373935 |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 May 2015 |accessdate=16 July 2015 |publisher=canadaam.ctvnews.ca |date=15 May 2015}}</ref> and overall the film received critical acclaim and became a box office success,<ref>{{cite web|title=Mad max Fury|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mad_max_fury_road/|publisher=rotten tomatoe|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> grossing over $378 million against a $150 million budget, becoming the highest-grossing film in the ''Mad Max'' franchise.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mad Max: Fury Road|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=furyroad.htm|publisher=box office mojo|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref>\nHe played a dual role as London gangsters [[Kray twins|Reggie and Ronnie Kray]] in the crime thriller ''[[Legend (2015 film)|Legend]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3569230/|title = Legend imbd|website = }}</ref> On 7 December 2015, Hardy won Best Actor at the [[British Independent Film Awards]] for his portrayal of the Kray twins, and on the same night attended the premiere of the biographical western thriller ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'', in which he co-stars with [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], at [[Odeon Leicester Square|Leicester Square]], London.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Hardy wins Best Actor at British Independent Film Awards|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/tvradio/news/story/2015/12/07/tom-hardy-wins-best-actor-at/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20151215112038/http://www.virginmedia.com/tvradio/news/story/2015/12/07/tom-hardy-wins-best-actor-at/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2015|date=11 December 2015}}</ref> On 14 January 2016, Hardy received his first [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for his performance in ''The Revenant''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2016|title=The 88th Academy Awards (2016) Nominees and Winners|accessdate=14 January 2016|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS)}}</ref>\n\nHardy played a [[Royal Air Force]] [[fighter pilot]] in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s action-thriller ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017), based on the British military [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuation of the French port of Dunkirk]] in 1940 during the [[World War II|Second World War]]. He appeared alongside [[Mark Rylance]], [[Kenneth Branagh]], [[Cillian Murphy]] and [[Harry Styles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/harry-styles-one-direction-christopher-nolan-dunkirk-1201728153/|title=Harry Styles, Fionn Whitehead to Star in Christopher Nolan WW2 Action-Thriller 'Dunkirk'|work=Variety|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=23 March 2016}}</ref> Hardy also co-produced and starred in the eight-part [[BBC One]] television drama series ''[[Taboo (2017 TV series)|Taboo]]''. It was created by Hardy, [[Steven Knight]], and Hardy's father, [[Chips Hardy|Edward \"Chips\" Hardy]]. ''Taboo'' was aired in the United States by [[FX (TV channel)|FX]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Swift|first1=Andy|title=Tom Hardy's FX/BBC One Drama ''Taboo'' Adds 13, Begins Production|url=http://tvline.com/2015/11/23/tom-hardy-taboo-fx-drama-cast-game-of-thrones-actors/|accessdate=11 August 2018|publisher=[[TVLine]]|date=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hardy starred in the film ''[[Venom (2018 film)|Venom]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbr.com/tom-hardy-signed-three-venom-movies/|title=Tom Hardy Is Signed for Three Venom Movies|date=25 August 2018|work=CBR|access-date=29 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/movies/video/tom-hardy-signed-for-three-venom-films/vi-BBMvOti|title=Tom Hardy signed for three Venom films|website=www.msn.com|language=en-US|access-date=29 August 2018}}</ref> as the title comic book sometime hero, [[Eddie Brock|Eddie Brock / Venom]]. Based on the [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] source material, the film was released on 5 October, and is meant to be the start of \"Sony's Universe Of Marvel Characters\" (along with ''[[Silver Sable#Film|Silver and Black]]''). It is connected to the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] as an \"adjunct\" film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/venom-silver-sable-spider-man-homecoming-movies-connections/|title=Venom & Black Cat Movies Will Be 'Adjuncts' to the MCU's Spider-Man|date=18 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/tom-hardy-venom-spinoff-spider-man-director-ruben-fleischer-1202418721/|title=Tom Hardy to Star in 'Spider-Man' Movie 'Venom,' Ruben Fleischer to Direct|work=Variety|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=10 October 2016}}</ref> In 2019, Hardy served as an executive producer in the 2019 [[BBC]]/[[FX (TV channel)|FX]] three-part miniseries ''[[A Christmas Carol (miniseries)|A Christmas Carol]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/steven-knight-a-christmas-carol-dickens-adaptations-bbc-ridley-scott-tom-hardy-1202215436/|title=Steven Knight To Adapt Charles Dickens Novels For BBC One; Ridley Scott, Tom Hardy Exec Producing|first1=Nancy|last1=Tartaglione|first2=Nancy|last2=Tartaglione|work=Deadline|date=28 November 2017|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/a-christmas-carol-tom-hardy-update-steven-knight/|title=Exclusive: Steven Knight Talks \u2018A Christmas Carol\u2019 with Tom Hardy & Teases Ambitious Dickens Plans|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|work=Collider|date=21 January 2019|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Upcoming projects===\nIn 2020, Hardy will star in [[Josh Trank]]'s [[Al Capone]] biopic ''[[Capone (2020 film)|Capone]].''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/tom-hardy-al-capone-movie-fonzo-josh-trank-1201845089/|title=Tom Hardy To Play Al Capone In New Movie \u2018Fonzo\u2019 From Josh Trank \u2013 AFM|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|work=Deadline|date=30 October 2016|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> Hardy is also attached to star as iconic war photographer [[Don McCullin]] in a film based on McCullin's autobiography, ''Unreasonable Behaviour''.<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/tom-hardy-war-photographer-don-mccullin-unreasonable-behaviour-working-title-1201777499/|author=Mike Fleming Jr|publisher=deadline.com|title=Tom Hardy To Play War Photographer Don McCullin In Working Title Drama &#124; Deadline|accessdate=12 November 2016|date=2016-06-22}}</ref> Hardy will reprise the role of Eddie Brock in the sequel ''[[Venom: Let There Be Carnage]]''.\n\n==Causes==\nIn 2010, Hardy became an ambassador for [[the Prince's Trust]], a leading UK youth charity which provides training, personal development, business start-up support, [[mentoring]], and advice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hollywood star Tom Hardy has paid a special visit to the capital to meet disadvantaged young people supported by The Prince's Trust|url=http://www.princes-trust.org.uk/about_the_trust/headline_news/news_2010/100526_hardy_is_ambassador.aspx|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> In 2012, he and then-girlfriend actress [[Charlotte Riley]] became patrons of Bowel Cancer UK.<ref>{{cite news|title=Actors Tom Hardy and Charlotte Riley become patrons of Bowel Cancer UK|url=http://www.bowelcanceruk.org.uk/media-centre/latest-news/tom-hardy-and-charlotte-riley-become-patrons/|accessdate=16 July 2015|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> Prior to the inaugural [[Invictus Games]] held in London in September 2014, he, along with other entertainers and athletes, read the poem \"[[Invictus]]\" in a promotional video.<ref>{{cite news|title=When are Prince Harry's Invictus Games and what are they?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/05/when-are-prince-harrys-invictus-games-and-what-are-they/|accessdate=2 October 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018 Hardy became lead ambassador<ref>{{cite web|title=Actor Tom Hardy Becomes Head Ambassador For REORG Jiu-Jitsu Foundation/|url=https://www.jiujitsutimes.com/actor-tom-hardy-becomes-head-ambassador-for-reorg-jiu-jitsu-foundation/|website=Actor Tom Hardy Becomes Head Ambassador For REORG Jiu-Jitsu Foundation/|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref> for the \"Reorg Brazilian Jiu Jitsu foundation\"<ref>{{cite web|title=the-reorg-jiu-jitsu-foundation/|url=https://theroyalmarinescharity.org.uk/news/the-reorg-jiu-jitsu-foundation/|website=the-reorg-jiu-jitsu-foundation/|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref> which was launched in association with The Royal Marines Charity with the mission to provide a platform for serving personnel and veterans to learn [[Brazilian Jiu Jitsu]], as part of their recovery pathway and to combat the challenge of mental health and physical disabilities. Hardy himself is a Brazilian Jiu Jitsu practitioner and has been seen training at [[Roger Gracie]] affiliate schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=tom-hardy-awarded-2nd-stripe-on-bjj-belt/|url=https://www.bjjee.com/articles/tom-hardy-awarded-2nd-stripe-on-bjj-belt/|website=BJJEE/|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Tom Hardy Locke Premiere.jpg|thumb|upright|Hardy at the premiere of ''[[Locke (film)|Locke]]'' in 2014]]\nHardy married producer Sarah Ward in 1999; they divorced in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Hardy & Charlotte Riley Are Expecting, & Their Children Are Going To Be So Beautiful|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/108561-tom-hardy-charlotte-riley-are-expecting-their-children-are-going-to-be-so-beautiful|work=Bustle|accessdate=7 January 2017|date=3 September 2015}}</ref> He has a son (born 2008)<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Hardy 'wasn't a fan of school'|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/tom-hardy-wasnt-a-fan-of-school-30095632.html|work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|accessdate=3 May 2014|date=14 March 2014}}</ref> with his then-girlfriend, [[assistant director]] Rachael Speed, whom he met on the set of ''[[The Virgin Queen (TV serial)|The Virgin Queen]]'' in 2005. They separated in 2009 after four years together.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Davies |first=Serena |title=Interview: Tom Hardy, from East End gangster to romantic hero |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=UK |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited |date=11 June 2009 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/5507365/Interview-Tom-Hardy-from-East-End-gangster-to-romantic-hero.html}}</ref> That same year, Hardy began a relationship with actress [[Charlotte Riley]], after they met on the set of ''[[Wuthering Heights (2009 TV serial)|Wuthering Heights]]''. They were married in July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Lauren Smith|title=Tom Hardy got married in secret - two months ago|url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/celebrity/2014/04/24/tom-hardy-secret-wedding-rumours-news|work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|accessdate=21 October 2014|date=22 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021200540/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/celebrity/2014/04/24/tom-hardy-secret-wedding-rumours-news#|archive-date=21 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In October 2015, their first child was born.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Hardy Expecting Second Child!|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/692639/tom-hardy-expecting-second-child-wife-charlotte-riley-is-pregnant-see-her-baby-bump|accessdate=3 September 2015|date=2015-09-03}}</ref> In December 2018 the couple's second child, a son, was born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/tom-hardy-charlotte-riley-baby-son-boy-forrest-gump-children-a8724341.html|title=Tom Hardy and Charlotte Riley 'name newborn son after Forrest Gump'|date=2019-01-11|website=The Independent|author=Sabrina Barr|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> They had two [[rescue dog]]s, Max and Woodstock, one of which Hardy appeared with in a [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] advert to promote [[pet adoption]].<ref>Rebecca Macatee, \"Tom Hardy Gets a Kiss From His Dog Woodstock in Pro-Adoption Campaign for PETA\u2014See the Pic!\" [http://www.eonline.com/news/650987/tom-hardy-gets-a-kiss-from-his-dog-woodstock-in-pro-adoption-campaign-for-peta-see-the-pic EOnline.com], 28 April 2015.</ref> Woodstock died on 5 June 2017 due to an aggressive case of [[polymyositis]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tomhardydotorg.tumblr.com/post/161532868851/i-first-saw-woodstock-running-across-a-turnpike-we|title=I first saw Woodstock running across a turnpike we... - tomhardydotorg|work=Tom Hardy Dot Org|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nHardy was named one of ''[[GQ]]'' magazine's 50 best-dressed British men in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=50 Best Dressed Men in Britain 2015|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107145128/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 January 2015|work=GQ|date=5 January 2015}}</ref> He appeared on [[Debrett's]] 2016 list of the most influential people in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Debrett's 500 List: Film|url=https://www.debretts.com/debretts-500-2016/list/|publisher=Debretys|date=21 May 2017}}</ref> Hardy was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2018 Birthday Honours]] for services to drama.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44397682|title=Dalglish and Thompson head honours list|date=8 June 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=8 June 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nHardy was addicted to alcohol and [[crack cocaine]] during his mid-20s, after which he checked himself into rehab following a particular low point. He has said that he was \"out of control\" on drink and drugs before he turned his life around, and was lucky that he did not contract [[HIV/AIDS]] while he was at his lowest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Hardy: I was lucky I didn't get AIDS from drug use|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/s/tom-hardy-was--out-of-control--on-drugs-and-alcohol-130033082.html|publisher=Yahoo!|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chrysaliscourses.ac.uk/news/actor-tom-hardy-reveals-past-addictions-still-haunt-him |title=Actor Tom Hardy reveals past addictions still haunt him |work=Chrysalis Courses |date= |accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the filming of ''[[Bronson (film)|Bronson]]'', Hardy met prisoner [[Charles Bronson (prisoner)|Charles Bronson]] several times and the two became friends. Bronson was impressed with how Hardy managed to get as muscular as he was and how well he could mimic his own personality and voice. Bronson stated that he believes Hardy was the only person who could play him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bronson - Tom Hardy Online|url=http://www.tom-hardy.co.uk/career/filmography/film-roles/bronson/|website=Tom Hardy Online|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT use \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Black Hawk Down (film)|Black Hawk Down]]''\n| Lance Twombly\n| Credited as Thomas Hardy\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''Deserter''\n| Pascal Dupont\n|\n